Introduction

Background

In recent years, artificial intelligence (AI) has shifted from a source of uncertainty and risk to a common feature of everyday life. From writing assistants and chat bots to algorithmic recommendations in education, finance, and entertainment, AI has become deeply embedded in social and professional contexts. Understanding how people perceive its benefits and risks is crucial for policymakers and organizations designing AI systems that are equitable and trustworthy. In recent years, artificial intelligence (AI) has undergone a profound shift in public perception. Once seen primarily as a source of uncertainty or even risk, AI is now becoming something people feel increasingly comfortable withif not socially or professionally expected to use. From writing assistants and chatbots to algorithmic recommendations in education, finance, and entertainment, AI has become an embedded feature of everyday life.

Dataset and preprocessing

To ground our analysis, we use the Public Attitudes to AI (PAI) data set produced by the Ada Lovelace Institute (UK). This nationally representative survey of approximately 4,000 adults captures attitudes toward AI across multiple domainssuch as hiring, healthcare, and policing. To ground our analysis, we use the Public Attitudes to AI dataset produced by the Ada Lovelace Institute (UK). This nationally representative survey of ~4,000 adults provides perceptions across multiple AI application domains. Our aim here is a reproducible initial exploration: inspect structure and missingness, perform light cleaning, compute simple summaries, and visualise perceived benefits of AI in hiring.

This project uses the preprocessed version of the data set provided by the Ada Lovelace Institute. Our group utilized similar cleaning techniques based on the descriptive analysis code by the Ada Lovelace Institute.

Goal: Our project aims to replicate the results of the Ada Lovelace Institution, but to also consider gender, age, and other demographics that impacted survey respondents perceived benefits of AI.

# Detect BENB-like columns and coerce to 0/1 integers where possible
benb_cols <- names(ai_clean)[str_detect(names(ai_clean), regex("^benb|benb_job|benefit|benefits|benb_", ignore_case = TRUE))]
if (length(benb_cols) == 0) {
  benb_cols <- names(ai_clean)[str_detect(names(ai_clean), regex("benefit|benb|job", ignore_case = TRUE))]
}

if (length(benb_cols) > 0) {
  ai_clean <- ai_clean %>%
    mutate(across(all_of(benb_cols), ~ {
      x <- .
      # character encodings -> 1/0
      if (is.character(x)) {
        xl <- str_to_lower(str_trim(x))
        as.integer(if_else(xl %in% c("yes","y","1","selected","true","t"), 1L,
                   if_else(xl %in% c("no","n","0","false","f"), 0L, NA_integer_)))
      } else if (is.logical(x)) {
        as.integer(x)
      } else {
        # numeric-like: keep 1/0, else NA
        xi <- suppressWarnings(as.integer(x))
        if_else(is.na(xi), NA_integer_, xi)
      }
    }))
}

The raw response data suggests that there is no single dominant theme in how the public perceives the benefits of AI. Instead, respondents highlight a wide range of advantages that span everyday life (e.g., vacuuming or unlocking devices), improved accessibility for people with disabilities, enhanced security of personal information, and support for public safety and border processes.

Overall, people seem to view AI as a set of practical tools that can make daily life a bit easier, safer, and more efficient. But, their perceived benefits are not focused on one area.

Looking deeper - AI Usage for Accessibility Purposes

Because the perceived benefits of AI span a variety of domains, we next focused our analysis on a specific application to better understand how attitudes differ across demographic groups. We selected Robo-vacuums and assistants as a case example: an everyday form of AI that can meaningfully improve accessibility, particularly for individuals with mobility limitations or other disabilities. Prior research has noted that assistive cleaning technologies can reduce physical strain and support independent living among vulnerable populations (Cleaning Is Caring, n.d.). By examining responses related to Robo-vacuum and robo-assistants , we explore whether age, gender, and other demographic characteristics influence who recognizes these accessibility-related benefits of AI.

  mutate(
    concerned = case_when(
      concern %in% c(1,2) ~ 1L,   # Very + Somewhat concerned
      concern %in% c(3,4,5) ~ 0L  # Not concerned + Don't know
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(age_group) %>%
  summarise(
    pct_concern = mean(concerned, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

ggplot(concern_age, aes(x = age_group, y = pct_concern, group = 1)) +
  
  geom_col(fill = "#D95F02", alpha = 0.7) +

  # Regression line
  geom_smooth(aes(x = as.numeric(age_group), y = pct_concern),
              method = "lm", se = FALSE,
              color = "black", size = 1,
              linetype = "dashed",
              inherit.aes = FALSE) +
  
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 1),
                     limits = c(0,1)) +
  
  labs(
    title = "Concern About Robotic Care Assistants by Age",
    subtitle = "Share of respondents who are very or somewhat concerned",
    x = "Age Group",
    y = "% Concerned"
  ) +

  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )

Concern about robotic care assistants increases with age, indicating that older respondents are especially wary of this technology. However, elevated concern is evident across all age groups, showing that unease toward robotic care assistants is a broadly shared sentiment and not exclusively an older-adult issue.

# Select all BENB_DC columns
benb_dc_data <- ai_clean %>%
  select(starts_with("benb_dc"))

# Convert to long format
benb_dc_long <- benb_dc_data %>%
  mutate(id = row_number()) %>%  # respondent ID
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("benb_dc"),
    names_to = "option",
    values_to = "selected"
  )

# Summarise counts and percentages
benb_dc_summary <- benb_dc_long %>%
  filter(!is.na(selected)) %>%
  group_by(option) %>%
  summarise(
    count = sum(selected == 1, na.rm = TRUE),
    total_respondents = n_distinct(id),
    percent = (count / total_respondents) * 100
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  # Clean up inconsistent naming
  mutate(
    option = tolower(option),
    option = str_replace_all(option, "benb[_]?dc[_]?", "benb_dc"),
    option = str_replace_all(option, "0+", "")
  ) %>%
  # Remove unwanted items
  filter(!option %in% c("benb_dc10", "benb_dc11")) %>%
  arrange(desc(percent))

# ---- PLOT ----
ggplot(benb_dc_summary, aes(x = reorder(option, percent), y = percent)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_x_discrete(
    labels = c(
      "benb_dc1" = "Easier car travel",
      "benb_dc2" = "More time for other activities",
      "benb_dc3" = "More accurate driving",
      "benb_dc4" = "Fewer accidents",
      "benb_dc5" = "Easier for disabled or older drivers",
      "benb_dc6" = "Saves money on drivers",
      "benb_dc7" = "Something else",
      "benb_dc8" = "None of these",
      "benb_dc9" = "Don't know"
    )
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Perceived Benefits of Driverless Cars",
    x = NULL,
    y = "Percentage of Respondents (%)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10),
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14)
  )
